What I Changed Compared to Your Two Separate Scripts

1.	Merged into one process — both an InputStream (capture → send) and an OutputStream (jitter buffer → playout) run simultaneously. <br />
2.	Two sockets instead of one shared socket — the original sender and receiver each bound to different ports (12345 for audio, 12346 for RTT). In the transceiver, both roles coexist, so: <br />
●	rx_sock binds to LOCAL_PORT (12345) — receives incoming audio from the remote peer, and echoes headers back for RTT. <br />
●	tx_sock binds to RTT_PORT (12346) — used by capture_callback to send audio out, and drained in the main loop for RTT echo replies. <br />
3.	Two device selections — calls select_backend('input') and select_backend('output') separately, so you can pick different devices/backends for mic vs speakers (e.g., ASIO input on Focusrite, WASAPI output on headphones). <br />
4.	Combined main-loop display — shows both [TX] and [RX] meters on each iteration, plus unified RTT, jitter buffer fill, and end-to-end estimate. <br />
5.	Full end-to-end latency estimate — the summary now includes both the input HW buffer and output HW buffer (the original receiver couldn't see the sender's input buffer since it was a separate process). <br />
<br />
Everything else — packet format, jitter buffer, callback architecture, RTT echo mechanism — is unchanged from your originals.
